               <interp inst="t18560514-502" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18560514"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18560514-502" type="date" value="18560514"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-502-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-502-18560514 t18560514-502-offence-1 t18560514-502-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>502. <persName id="def1-502-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-502-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-502-18560514" type="age" value="21"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-502-18560514" type="surname" value="GOURD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-502-18560514" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES GOURD</hi>,</persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-502-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-502-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-502-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp> Burglariously breaking and entering the dwell<lb></lb>ing house of <persName id="t18560514-name-265" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-265" type="surname" value="ASHLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-265" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-502-offence-1 t18560514-name-265"></join>Edward Ashley</persName>, and stealing 1 clock, 2 table covers, 1 bird<lb></lb>cage, and other goods, value 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; his property.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CAARTEEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-266" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-266" type="surname" value="COX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-266" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COX</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">policeman, N</hi> 369). I met the prisoner, about a quarter before 6 o'clock in the morning, on 11th April, at the top of Canonbury-street, Lower-road, Islington—he was carrying a birdcage with two birds in it—I followed him as far as Queen-street, about 200 or 300 yards, stopped him, and asked where he brought the birdcage from—he said, "If you win come with me, I will show you"—I went with him about two yards, when he dropped the cage at my feet, and ran away—I pursued him about a dozen yards, when he turned round, drew a knife from his pocket, and said, "You b—, if you come nigh me, you will have it"—he then con<lb></lb>tinued running till I stopped him again, about a dozen yards further—before I secured him he turned round several times, and attempted to stab me time after time—at the corner of George-street he took two tablecloths from his waistcoat—he threw one on a wall, with intent to throw it into a garden, and the other he threw in the middle of the road—he then ran about fifty yards further—he then dropped the knife, and I secured him—another policeman came to my assistance, and we searched the prisoner, and found this piece of ribbon in his waistcoat pocket—I got one of the table-cloths—a butcher came by, and took one, and ran away with it—I have not the least doubt that the prisoner is the man I saw with the birdcage—I never lost sight of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How far is the place where you saw him with the birdcage, from where he was taken? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About half a mile—when he threw the cloths away, he buttoned up his clothes, and said, "Now come on," and he ran some distance, and dropped the knife, and I took him—it was fifty or sixty yards from where the things were thrown down to where he was taken—I did not lose sight of him till I took him—Atkins saw the whole of it—I never saw Atkins before—I believe he has been a witness in one case before—he is not an amateur policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-267" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-267" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-267" type="surname" value="ATKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-267" type="given" value="JABEZ"></interp>JABEZ ATKINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in New Norfolk-street, and am a cowman. I was in Queen-street about a quarter past 6 o'clock in the morning on 11th April—I saw the prisoner in Lower Queen-street, carrying a birdcage under his arm—I saw Cox go up to him—the prisoner put the cage dow</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140244"></xptr>
               <p>at his feet, and ran away—Cox ran after him—I joined in the pursuit—the prisoner was stopped at the end of George-street—before he was stopped I saw he had a knife in his hand, and he kept running at the policeman—the policeman sprang his rattle—I went towards the prisoner, and he said, "What the b—hell do you want P—he had part of a brick in his hand—I saw these tablecloths up above his waistcoat, and he threw one on the wall at Mr. Fowler's, the corner of Rotherfield-street, and I saw another tablecloth lying at the corner of Halliford-street, by which the prisoner ran—I left Cox before the prisoner was taken—I saw him taken into custody when I returned—the sergeant was running along with me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When did you first see the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> When I was putting the horse to the cart—I had seen the policeman on the same beat for about two months before—I am quite sure the prisoner is the man who had the birdcage—he took the cloths out of his waistcoat in George-street—one he threw on the wall—I went away, and got assistance—I am quite sure the man I saw throw the things away was the same man I after<lb></lb>wards saw in custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-268" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-268" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-268" type="surname" value="ASHLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-268" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD ASHLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 4, Clifton-villas, Grange-road, about three minutes' walk from the top of Canonbury-street. On Thursday night, 10th April, I went to bed, a few minutes alter 10 o'clock—the window of the dining room was not closed within half an inch—the servant had had the sash down in the day, and we could not get it up—the door of the dining room was locked outside—I was alarmed about hall past 6 o'clock next morning—I went into the dining room, and found the window open wide, and the things in great confusion—some boxes, the cheffonier, and other things, were broken open—there had been two cages there, which had one bird in each; one cage was left, but the bird had been taken out of it, and put into the cage which was missing—that cage was afterwards shown to me, it was mine, and the birds, which had been in my room—I missed two tablecloths, this is one of them—on the Thursday night this was with the other, folded up, and put on a chair in the dining room—I can identify this piece of blue silk, it was in my wife's workbox the night before—my house is in the parish of St. Mary, Islington.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How can you venture to swear to a bit of silk in your wife's workbox? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the afternoon before I was very unwell, lying on the sofa, and my little girl was unpicking this from another piece—I have fitted it, to see that it corresponds—I am a lock manufacturer by business—I mean to say that this was in my wife's box—I have not had this compared with the article it was upon, but I did it in my eye.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How was the dining room door in the morning? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was locked, in the same state as it was the night before—it had not been interfered with.</p>
               <p>
